[Pico do Itabira], 1843, 
<emphasis id="7904C35AC2D7458BB3A5B4436EF525C4" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Claussen 392</emphasis>
(P00743993!).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B1D99AA2E9407DA09EAB44B46CA345C1" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" type="description">
<paragraph id="DFF8B6E968FA9617BEDEA72D8BD0C4B3" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="76690A359F47DEC41D2C291827EF4042" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
Annual or short-lived perennial herb with several or numerous stems 10-40 cm high; leaves sessile (sometimes rosulate leaves shortly pedunculate), cuneate, 10-30 mm long and 0.3-3.0(5.0) mm wide; inflorescence a spike; pedicels 1.35-1.7(2.5) mm; flowers with a bract and two bracteoles, perianth segments 5, white, oblong; stamens 6-8, stigmas 3-5, thin; fruit 0.9-1.1 
<normalizedToken id="2FD09B8A77E870DD5B0A1CBDE6E24AA2" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1.0-1.1 mm (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="872D48E9E58D38F27C3A68A0DE1452D1" captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Fruits and seeds of Microtea maypurensis and M. tenuifolia: A, B fruit of M. maypurensis, enclosed in the perianth (Bolivia, La Paz Dept., Beni river, Jul 1886, H. H. Rusby 1379, LE) C, D seed of M. maypurensis (Bolivia, La Paz Dept., Beni river, Jul 1886, H. H. Rusby 1379, LE) E, F fruit of M. tenuifolia enclosed in the perianth (Brazil, Minas Gerais, Serrra das Vertentes, Jun 1893, A. Glaziou 20437, B) G, H seed of M. tenuifolia (Brazil, Jacobina Mountains in Bahia, 1836, Blanchet 2588, P 00798998). Magnification: A, E - 30 x, B, F - 100 x, C, G - 50 x, D, H - 300 x." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.115.29041.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/255661" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">8E</figureCitation>
), equal to perianth or slightly protruding; pericarp smooth or with small and scattered tubercles (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="795D0C7D6F80AD126435EE6FEDF76226" captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Fruits and seeds of Microtea maypurensis and M. tenuifolia: A, B fruit of M. maypurensis, enclosed in the perianth (Bolivia, La Paz Dept., Beni river, Jul 1886, H. H. Rusby 1379, LE) C, D seed of M. maypurensis (Bolivia, La Paz Dept., Beni river, Jul 1886, H. H. Rusby 1379, LE) E, F fruit of M. tenuifolia enclosed in the perianth (Brazil, Minas Gerais, Serrra das Vertentes, Jun 1893, A. Glaziou 20437, B) G, H seed of M. tenuifolia (Brazil, Jacobina Mountains in Bahia, 1836, Blanchet 2588, P 00798998). Magnification: A, E - 30 x, B, F - 100 x, C, G - 50 x, D, H - 300 x." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.115.29041.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/255661" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">8F</figureCitation>
), more or less reticulate, readily scraped off the seed; seed 0.9-1.1 mm, with rough surface (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="B8903EE59CCF223F3FC9B0BF060F508F" captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Fruits and seeds of Microtea maypurensis and M. tenuifolia: A, B fruit of M. maypurensis, enclosed in the perianth (Bolivia, La Paz Dept., Beni river, Jul 1886, H. H. Rusby 1379, LE) C, D seed of M. maypurensis (Bolivia, La Paz Dept., Beni river, Jul 1886, H. H. Rusby 1379, LE) E, F fruit of M. tenuifolia enclosed in the perianth (Brazil, Minas Gerais, Serrra das Vertentes, Jun 1893, A. Glaziou 20437, B) G, H seed of M. tenuifolia (Brazil, Jacobina Mountains in Bahia, 1836, Blanchet 2588, P 00798998). Magnification: A, E - 30 x, B, F - 100 x, C, G - 50 x, D, H - 300 x." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.115.29041.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/255661" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">8H</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9090B36E03AD3404E0D9A6823E4E3369" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
We report for the first time that the perianth/fruit ratio is a useful distinguishing character for this species. Also, the number of stigmas can be useful in delimiting 
<taxonomicName id="E215A969899357F5137BECFCE7EAB4A1" authorityName="Moq. in DC., Prodr. 13 (2): 18" authorityYear="1849" family="Microteaceae" genus="M." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. tenuifolia" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" rank="species" species="tenuifolia">
<emphasis id="EEE5D62564D02C10750A4E73E680CFA0" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">M. tenuifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and similar forms of 
<taxonomicName id="2C4A8D8C8309A0406C357BA278756476" family="Microteaceae" genus="M." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. celosioides" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" rank="species" species="celosioides">
<emphasis id="988940570895E653EA673D3418D99077" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">M. celosioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with narrower leaves. The character set of 
<taxonomicName id="DABF05F2C37565AB8D0C9900D5836BCD" authorityName="Moq. in DC., Prodr. 13 (2): 18" authorityYear="1849" family="Microteaceae" genus="M." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. tenuifolia" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" rank="species" species="tenuifolia">
<emphasis id="1E52E32AD1C4A75C6DA1FDD2EE3CC207" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">M. tenuifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
supports its close relationship to 
<taxonomicName id="538DDAD8B3DDC6F39776E32F100361E3" authorityName="G. Don, Hort. Brit. [Loudon]: 98" authorityYear="1830" baseAuthorityName="Kunth" family="Microteaceae" genus="M." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. maypurensis" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" rank="species" species="maypurensis">
<emphasis id="D85E8985FB072C715F32A72FC4387B7B" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">M. maypurensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, especially the forms with reduced pericarp outgrowths. Remarkably, 
<bibRefCitation id="4EF28DA67582CACC573434D19F886D3E" author="Moquin-Tandon, A" editor="De Candolle, A" journalOrPublisher="13, pt. 2. V. Masson, Paris" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" pagination="3 - 40" refId="B34" refString="Moquin-Tandon, A, 1849. Phytolaccaceae. In: De Candolle, A, Ed., Prodromus systematis universalis regni vegetabilis, Vol. 13, pt. 2. V. Masson, Paris: 3 - 40" title="Phytolaccaceae." volumeTitle="Prodromus systematis universalis regni vegetabilis, Vol." year="1849">Moquin-Tandon (1849)</bibRefCitation>
described a new variety of 
<taxonomicName id="F1A92E525D8EE837362E5CAAF2420C37" authorityName="G. Don, Hort. Brit. [Loudon]: 98" authorityYear="1830" baseAuthorityName="Kunth" family="Microteaceae" genus="M." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. maypurensis" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" rank="species" species="maypurensis">
<emphasis id="CA65184C5C5195FAD2FD0564C7E80BA6" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">M. maypurensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(var. 
<taxonomicName id="882E416A376DA23445AEC0432A4B7166" family="Microteaceae" genus="M." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="var. angustifolia" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" rank="variety" species="maypurensis" variety="angustifolia">angustifolia</taxonomicName>
Moq.) represented by two specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="D74D600BF60933FA0C56E1A4ACE4FCD4" authorityName="Moq. in DC., Prodr. 13 (2): 18" authorityYear="1849" family="Microteaceae" genus="M." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. tenuifolia" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" rank="species" species="tenuifolia">
<emphasis id="AE1E569D473B0796A8E43FCCEF87A052" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">M. tenuifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(P00743955! and P00798998!) and one specimen containing two individuals, 
<taxonomicName id="6EDD2105EB41B8D4A89203D0AD312CCB" authorityName="Moq. in DC., Prodr. 13 (2): 18" authorityYear="1849" family="Microteaceae" genus="M." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. tenuifolia" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" rank="species" species="tenuifolia">
<emphasis id="EB7B5FB5EB74A6A9BA321B0EE4EDC007" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">M. tenuifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and a narrow-leaved 
<taxonomicName id="C3585C44CC72EE835FADFC1A97F45592" authorityName="G. Don, Hort. Brit. [Loudon]: 98" authorityYear="1830" baseAuthorityName="Kunth" family="Microteaceae" genus="M." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. maypurensis" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" rank="species" species="maypurensis">
<emphasis id="3432E4B8ECC96179EA04F90D65E301AF" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">M. maypurensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(leg. 
<emphasis id="6DDF77EA20607B438948AA14C657B8E1" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Blanchet 2588</emphasis>
, P00743954!). The figure of 
<taxonomicName id="B4728C8CB6CF8976324A86F8E7A58E96" authorityName="Moq. in DC., Prodr. 13 (2): 18" authorityYear="1849" family="Microteaceae" genus="M." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. tenuifolia" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" rank="species" species="tenuifolia">
<emphasis id="09E938F914238628FB3AA367CA6BA9F9" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">M. tenuifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<bibRefCitation id="5B592A8E81ED4BBE8AE0978426F4DAC0" author="Calio, MF" journalOrPublisher="Universidade de Sao Paulo" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" pagination="15 - 16" refId="B11" refString="Calio, MF, Pirani, JR, 2006. Flora de Grao Mogol, Minas Gerais: Phytolaccaceae. Boletim de Botanica, Departamento de Botanica. Instituto de Biociencias. Universidade de Sao Paulo 24: 15 - 16" title="Flora de Grao Mogol, Minas Gerais: Phytolaccaceae. Boletim de Botanica, Departamento de Botanica. Instituto de Biociencias." volume="24" year="2006">
<normalizedToken id="63C8C72FEC8989B4A78B8369DA894892" originalValue="Calió">Calio</normalizedToken>
and Pirani (2006)
</bibRefCitation>
showing the tuberculate perianth is rather an exception, and the individuals with pericarp lacking the outgrowths have so far been collected more frequently.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8CA45A3784DB95218395BF03996C08C7" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" type="habitat">
<paragraph id="F6D892CFA3ABA1EE42739E7A191A6320" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DBA24701A47728453CC007DD0788B8E6" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Forest margins, rocky places; 0-1000 m.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="120EE46B92D289196DC6FC65A75BCBB8" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="5F3A26B25FC463D345F4D51D0F61567C" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<pageBreakToken id="9F1B8ABFBF219969D888DE1A31687E08" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" start="start">Distribution</pageBreakToken>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="EA57573C3F2C83ED14D9796E91F510D1" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
Endemic to Eastern Brazil, found only in Bahia, 
<normalizedToken id="B2E12EBA54C2BCAD6F24BAD68453B662" originalValue="Espírito">Espirito</normalizedToken>
Santo, Minas Gerais and Rio de Janeiro States (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="D725F6359C593D918B0ECB215C73FEF6" captionStart="Figure 25" captionStartId="F25" captionText="Figure 25. Distribution map of Microtea tenuifolia." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.115.29041.figure25" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/255678" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">25</figureCitation>
